data.title: Athletes Born on November 23
data.meta_description: Famous birthdays in sport for the 23rd of November. Browse birthdays of sports stars, managers and coaches that were born on November 23.
data.text:
Thomas Lord, English cricket batsman (founder of Lord's cricket ground; Middlesex CCC), born in Thirsk, England (d. 1832)

James Lillywhite, English cricket slow bowler (1st England Test captain; 2 Tests, 8 wickets; Sussex CCC) and umpire (6 Tests 1881–99), born in Westhampnett, England (d. 1929)

Frank Hearne, English cricket batsman (2 Tests England, 4 South Africa; Kent, Western Province), born in Ealing, England (d. 1949)

Howard Taylor, American tennis player (US National C'ships doubles 1879; singles 1884, 86, 87, 88 runner-up), born in New York City (d. 1920)

Holcombe Ward, American tennis player (US Nat C'ship 1904; President USLTA 1937-47), born in New York, NY (d. 1967)

Harry Sunderland, Australian rugby league administrator (manager 1929–30 Kangaroo tour of GB; Queensland RFL secretary 1913-22; inspired establishment RL in France), born in Gympie, Australia (d. 1964)

Hal Schumacher, American baseball pitcher (World Series 1933; MLB All-Star 1933, 35; New York Giants), born in Hinkley, New York (d. 1993)

Emmett Ashford, American baseball umpire (first certified black umpire), born in Los Angeles, California (d. 1980)

Billy Haughton, American harness driver and trainer (Hambletonian x 4; Little Brown Jug x 5; Messenger Stakes x 7), born in Gloversville, NY (d. 1986)

Maurice Flitcroft, British golfer known as "the world's worst golfer", born in Manchester, England (d. 2007)

Dick Kazmaier, American College Football Hall of Fame halfback (Heisman Trophy 1951; Unanimous All-American 1951; Princeton), born in Maumee, Ohio (d. 2013)

1930 Jack McKeon, American baseball manager (World Series 2003, Florida Marlins; 2 × NL Manager of the Year 1999, 2003), born in South Amboy, New Jersey

Yevgeny Grischin, Russian 500m/1500m speed skater (Olympic gold 1956, 60), born in Tula, Soviet Union (d. 2005)

Lew Hoad

Australian tennis player (Wimbledon 1956-57, Australian C'ships 1956, French C'ships 1956)), born in Sydney, NSW

Steve Burtenshaw, English soccer manager (Sheffield Wednesday, Everton, QPR, Arsenal) and midfielder (Brighton & HA 237 games), born in Portslade, England (d. 2022)

1935 Wally Harris, Canadian ice hockey referee (6 x Stanley Cup series; first NHL Director of Officiating), born in Montreal, Quebec (d. 2024)

Bev Risman, English rugby union fly-half (8 Tests England, 4 British & Irish Lions; University of Oxford RFC) and rugby league fullback (5 Tests GB, 1 England; Leigh RLFC, Leeds RLFC), born in Salford, England (d. 2023)

Gene Visscher, American college basketball coach (Weber State University 1971-74; Northern Arizona University 1981-83), born in Muskegon, Michigan (d. 2022)

1940 Luis Tiant, Cuban baseball pitcher (MLB All-Star 1968, 74, 76), born in Marianao, Cuba

Alan Mullery, English soccer player (Fulham, Spurs), manager and pundit, born in London, England

1941 Simon Nolet, French Canadian NHL hockey right winger, 1967-77 (Stanley Cup - 1974, Philadelphia Flyers, and 3 other teams), born in Saint-Odilon-de-Cranbourne, Quebec, Canada

Petar Skansi, Croatian basketball center (Olympic silver Yugoslavia 1968; Jugoplastika) and coach (Yugoslavia, Croatia, Jugoplastika, Benetton Treviso), born in Sumartin, Croatia (d. 2022)

Giorgos Koudas, Greek footballer, born in Thessaloniki, Greece

Frank Worthington, English soccer forward (8 caps; Huddersfield Town, Leicester City, Bolton Wanderers) and manager (Tranmere Rovers), born in Halifax, England (d. 2021)

Bernd Landvoigt, German coxless pairs rower (Olympic gold 1976), born in Brandenburg an der Havel, German Democratic Republic

1951 Jorg Landvoigt, German coxless pairs rower (Olympic gold 1976), born in Brandenburg an der Havel, German Democratic Republic

Francie Larrieu Smith, American 1.5/3/10K track runner (AAU 1 mile-1979), born in Palo Alto, California

Martin Kent, Australian cricketer (Queensland batsman, Australia)

Glenn Brummer, American baseball player, born in Olney, Illinois

1954 Ken Schrom, American MLB player, born in Grangeville, Idaho

Bruce Edgar, New Zealand cricketer (NZ opener through the 80's), born in Wellington, New Zealand

Shane Gould

Australian freestyle swimmer (Olympic-3 gold-1972), born in Sydney, Australia

Martin Snedden, New Zealand cricket seam bowler (25 Tests, 58 wickets, BB 5/68; Auckland) and executive (CEO NZC 2001-11), born in Auckland, New Zealand

Brook Jacoby, American baseball third baseman (MLB All Star 1986, 90 Cleveland Indians), born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania

Jayananda Warnaweera, Sri Lankan cricketer (Sri Lankan fastish off-spin bowler), born in Matara, Sri Lanka

Merv Hughes, Australian cricket fast bowler (53 Tests, 212 wickets; 33 ODIs), born in Euroa, Australia

Dale Sveum, American MLB player and coach, born in Richmond, California

Dan Snyder, American NFL team owner (Washington Football Team), born in Silver Spring, Maryland

1964 Frank Rutherford, Bahamian athlete

1964 Jose Gonzales, baseball MLB player, born in Puerto Plata, Dominican Republic

1964 Kapila Wijegunewardene, Sri Lankan cricketer (fast-medium bowler), born in Colombo, Sri Lanka

Rodion Gataullin, Uzbekistan pole vaulter (Olympic silver 1988)

Jerry Kelly, American golfer (3 PGA Tour titles), born in Madison, Wisconsin

Brian Glynn, German NHL defenseman (Hartford Whalers), born in Iserlohn, West Germany

1967 Gary Kirsten, South African cricket batsman and coach (101 Tests, 7,289 runs @ 45.27, 21 x 100s), born in Cape Town, South Africa

Jim Pyne, American NFL guard/corner (Tampa Bay Bucs), born in Milford, Massachusetts

1971 Vin Baker, American NBA forward (Seattle Supersonics, Milwaukee Bucks), born in Lake Wales, Florida

Joeli Vidiri, Fijian rugby union winger (7 Tests Fiji, 2 New Zealand; Auckland RU, Barbarian FC), born in Nausori, Fiji (d. 2022)

1973 Reggie Green, NFL guard (Seattle Seahawks), born in Chattanooga, Tennessee

Jamie Sharper, linebacker (Baltimore Ravens), born in Richmond, Virginia

1974 Malik Rose, NBA forward (San Antonio Spurs), born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania

1974 Saku Koivu, NHL left wing (Montreal Canadiens, Olympic bronze 1998), born in Turku, Finland

1974 Tora Suber, WNBA guard (Charlotte Sting), born in Coatesville, Pennsylvania

1974 Tyrus McCloud, American football linebacker (Baltimore Ravens), born in Fort Lauderdale, Florida

Adam Eaton, American baseball player, born in Springfield, Ohio

1977 Myriam Boileau, Canadian diver, born in Montreal, Quebec

Jonathan Papelbon, American baseball player, born in Baton Rouge, Louisiana

Asafa Powell, Jamaican sprinter, born in Spanish Town, Jamaica

1982 Colby Armstrong, Canadian ice-hockey player, born in Lloydminster, Canada

Justin Turner, American baseball 3rd baseman (MLB All-Star 2017, 21; World Series 2020; NLCS MVP 2017; Los Angeles Dodgers), born in Long Beach, California

Ahn Hyun-Soo, South Korean short track skater, born in Seoul, South Korea

Nicklas Bäckström, Swedish ice hockey center (World C'ship gold 2006, 17; Stanley Cup 2018; NHL All Star 2016; Washington Capitals, born in Valbo, Sweden

Gabriel Landeskog, Swedish ice hockey left wing (captain Colorado Avalanche Stanley Cup 2022; World C'ship gold 2013, 17; Calder Trophy 2012; NHL All Star 2019), born in Stockholm, Sweden

Ariya Jatanugarn, Thai golfer (British Open 2016, US Open 2018), born in Bangkok, Thailand
